{"title_page": "Number 16 (spider)", "text_new": "{{Infobox animal\n| name                    = Number 16\n| image                   = \n| image_size              = \n| caption                 = \n| species                 = ''[[Gaius villosus]]''\n| gender                  = Female\n| birth_date              = 1974\n| birth_place             = North Bungulla Reserve, [[Western Australia]]\n| death_date              = 2016 (aged about 43)\n| death_place             = North Bungulla Reserve, [[Western Australia]]\n| resting_place           =\n| known                   = Subject of long-term monitoring project; oldest known spider<ref name=2018paper/>}}\n\n'''Number 16''' (1974 \u2013 2016), also known as '''#16''',<ref name=2018paper/> was a wild female [[armored trapdoor spider|trapdoor spider]] (''[[Gaius villosus]],'' family [[Idiopidae]]) that lived in North Bungulla Reserve near [[Tammin, Western Australia]]. She died in 2016, at an estimated age of 43 years, and is the longest-lived [[spider]] recorded to date.<ref name=2018paper/> Number 16 did not die of old age, but was most likely killed by a parasitic [[spider wasp|wasp]] sting.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/apr/30/worlds-oldest-known-spider-dies-at-43-after-a-quiet-life-underground/|title=World's oldest known spider dies at 43 after a quiet life underground|first=Agence |last=France-Presse|date=30 April 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Long-term monitoring==\nNumber 16 was born in 1974, and was studied in the wild by arachnologist [[Barbara York Main]] from March 1974 until 2016.<ref name=2018paper>{{cite journal|last1=Mason|first1=Leanda Denise|last2=Wardell-Johnson|first2=Grant|last3=Main|first3=Barbara York|title=The longest-lived spider: mygalomorphs dig deep, and persevere|journal=Pacific Conservation Biology|volume=24|issue=2|pages=203|date=2018|doi=10.1071/PC18015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/2018/04/27/farewell-no-16-scientists-left-miserable-worlds-oldest-spider/|title=Farewell, No. 16: scientists left 'miserable' after world's oldest spider dies aged 43|first=Henry|last=Bodkin|date=27 April 2018|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/number-16-worlds-oldest-known-spider-dies-aged-43-2676125|title=Number 16, World's Oldest Known Spider, Dies Aged 43|date=28 April 2018|website=ibtimes.com}}</ref> She was part of the first cohort of dispersing spiderlings to establish a burrow at the study site, and her burrow was the 16th to be marked with a peg.<ref name=2018paper/> By 1978, Main had tagged 101 burrows at the study site, within a few metres of each other.<ref name=WP/>\n\nNumber 16 spent her entire life in the same [[burrow]], which is typical for her species.<ref name=Guardian/> For over 40 years, her status was monitored by Main and her collaborators either six-monthly or annually.<ref name=2018paper/> As Number 16 became older, the researchers developed a tradition of always checking her burrow first when they visited the site.<ref name=WP/>\n\n==Death==\nOn 31 October 2016, researcher Leanda Mason discovered Number 16's burrow in disrepair, and the spider missing.<ref name=WP>Avi Selk (2018) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2018/05/01/the-extraordinary-life-and-death-of-the-worlds-oldest-known-spider/ \"The extraordinary life and death of the world\u2019s oldest known spider\"] ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 1 May 2018. Accessed 2 May 2018.</ref> The silk plug of her burrow had been pierced by a parasitic [[spider wasp]], suggesting that she had been parasitised, either before or after death.<ref name=2018paper/> During a survey six months earlier, Number 16 had been alive.<ref name=2018paper/> \u201cShe was cut down in her prime [...] It took a while to sink in, to be honest,\" said Mason.<ref name=WP/>  The spider's death received widespread publicity in late April 2018, with the publication of a research article in the journal ''[[Pacific Conservation Biology]]''.<ref name=2018paper/> Based on the burrow fidelity of females of her species, the researchers concluded with a \"high level of certainty\" that Number 16 was 43 years old at the time of her death.<ref name=2018paper/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:16, Number}}\n[[Category:Individual animals in Australia]]\n[[Category:1974 animal births]]\n[[Category:Spiders of Australia]]\n[[Category:2016 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:Idiopidae]]\n[[Category:Oldest animals]]\n[[Category:Individual wild animals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox animal\n| name                    = Number 16\n| image                   = \n| image_size              = \n| caption                 = \n| species                 = ''[[Gaius villosus]]''\n| gender                  = Female\n| birth_date              = 1974\n| birth_place             = North Bungulla Reserve, [[Western Australia]]\n| death_date              = 2016 (aged about 43)\n| death_place             = North Bungulla Reserve, [[Western Australia]]\n| resting_place           =\n| known                   = Subject of long-term monitoring project; oldest known spider<ref name=2018paper/>}}\n\n'''Number 16''' (1974 \u2013 2016), also known as '''#16,'''<ref name=2018paper/> was a wild female [[armored trapdoor spider|trapdoor spider]] (''[[Gaius villosus]],'' family [[Idiopidae]]) that lived in North Bungulla Reserve near [[Tammin, Western Australia]]. She died in 2016, at an estimated age of 43 years, and is the longest-lived [[spider]] recorded to date.<ref name=2018paper/> Number 16 did not die of old age, but was most likely killed by a parasitic [[spider wasp|wasp]] sting.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/apr/30/worlds-oldest-known-spider-dies-at-43-after-a-quiet-life-underground/|title=World's oldest known spider dies at 43 after a quiet life underground|first=Agence |last=France-Presse|date=30 April 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Long-term monitoring==\nNumber 16 was born in 1974, and was studied in the wild by arachnologist [[Barbara York Main]] from March 1974 until 2016.<ref name=2018paper>{{cite journal|last1=Mason|first1=Leanda Denise|last2=Wardell-Johnson|first2=Grant|last3=Main|first3=Barbara York|title=The longest-lived spider: mygalomorphs dig deep, and persevere|journal=Pacific Conservation Biology|volume=24|issue=2|pages=203|date=2018|doi=10.1071/PC18015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/2018/04/27/farewell-no-16-scientists-left-miserable-worlds-oldest-spider/|title=Farewell, No. 16: scientists left 'miserable' after world's oldest spider dies aged 43|first=Henry|last=Bodkin|date=27 April 2018|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/number-16-worlds-oldest-known-spider-dies-aged-43-2676125|title=Number 16, World's Oldest Known Spider, Dies Aged 43|date=28 April 2018|website=ibtimes.com}}</ref> She was part of the first cohort of dispersing spiderlings to establish a burrow at the study site, and her burrow was the 16th to be marked with a peg.<ref name=2018paper/> By 1978, Main had tagged 101 burrows at the study site, within a few metres of each other.<ref name=WP/>\n\nNumber 16 spent her entire life in the same [[burrow]], which is typical for her species.<ref name=Guardian/> For over 40 years, her status was monitored by Main and her collaborators either six-monthly or annually.<ref name=2018paper/> As Number 16 became older, the researchers developed a tradition of always checking her burrow first when they visited the site.<ref name=WP/>\n\n==Death==\nOn 31 October 2016, researcher Leanda Mason discovered Number 16's burrow in disrepair, and the spider missing.<ref name=WP>Avi Selk (2018) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2018/05/01/the-extraordinary-life-and-death-of-the-worlds-oldest-known-spider/ \"The extraordinary life and death of the world\u2019s oldest known spider\"] ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 1 May 2018. Accessed 2 May 2018.</ref> The silk plug of her burrow had been pierced by a parasitic [[spider wasp]], suggesting that she had been parasitised, either before or after death.<ref name=2018paper/> During a survey six months earlier, Number 16 had been alive.<ref name=2018paper/> \u201cShe was cut down in her prime [...] It took a while to sink in, to be honest,\" said Mason.<ref name=WP/>  The spider's death received widespread publicity in late April 2018, with the publication of a research article in the journal ''[[Pacific Conservation Biology]]''.<ref name=2018paper/> Based on the burrow fidelity of females of her species, the researchers concluded with a \"high level of certainty\" that Number 16 was 43 years old at the time of her death.<ref name=2018paper/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:16, Number}}\n[[Category:Individual animals in Australia]]\n[[Category:1974 animal births]]\n[[Category:Spiders of Australia]]\n[[Category:2016 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:Idiopidae]]\n[[Category:Oldest animals]]\n[[Category:Individual wild animals]]\n", "name_user": "Ackatsis", "label": "safe", "comment": "bolding", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_16_(spider)"}
